47","1035":"1035","1045":"1045","Falaise, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Falaise, Calvados, Normandie, Frankrijk","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Europe":"Europa","Salisbury, Wiltshire, England":"Salisbury, Wiltshire, England"},"en":{"1050–":"1050–Deceased","1047–1080":"1047–1080","1050–Female":"1050–Deceased","1052–1096":"1052–1096","1045–1086":"1045–1086","1070–1130":"1070–1130","1072–Female":"1072–Deceased","1074–Male":"1074–Deceased","1020–1070":"1020–1070","1035–1080":"1035–1080","about 1072":"about 1072","1080":"1080","about 1063":"about 1063","about 1074":"about 1074","before 1038":"before 1038","1066":"1066","1020":"1020","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1074":"1074","1096":"1096","1052":"1052","1050":"1050","1072":"1072","1070":"1070","1047":"1047","1035":"1035","1045":"1045","Falaise, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Falaise, Calvados, Normandy, France","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Europe":"Europe","Salisbury, Wiltshire, England":"Salisbury, Wiltshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Derbyshire","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Derbyshire (see   Darby  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Darby","meanings":["English: habitational name from the city of Derby, the county seat of Derbyshire, but also from the much smaller place called West Derby in Lancashire. Both are named from Old Norse <i>djúr</i> ‘deer’ + <i>bȳ</i> ‘farm, settlement’. This form of the surname represents the pronunciation of both the placename and the surname.","Irish: adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Diarmada</b> (or <b>Mac Diarmada</b>) ‘descendant (or ‘son’) of <i>Diarmaid</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘freeman’. See also   Dermott  ,   McDermott  . Gaelic <b>Ó Duibhdhiormaigh</b> was sometimes reinterpreted as <b>Ó Diarmada</b>, and Darby could also be an Anglicized form of this name. The English surname is also established in Ireland, having been taken to County Leix in the 16th century."]},{"name":"Darbyshire","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Derbyshire  . This form of the surname represents the pronunciation of both the county name and the surname."]}]},{"name":"Mathilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":16,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":36,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":46,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilda de Derbyshire was born in 1050, in Derbyshire, England, her father, William F. de Derbyshire, was 31 and her mother, Lady P De Normandie, was 15. She married Ranulph Fitz-Hubert de Rie about 1063, in Falaise, Calvados, Normandy, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in Salisbury, Wiltshire, England."},"et":{"1050–":"1050–Surnud","1047–1080":"1047–1080","1050–Female":"1050–Surnud","1052–1096":"1052–1096","1045–1086":"1045–1086","1070–1130":"1070–1130","1072–Female":"1072–Surnud","1074–Male":"1074–Surnud","1020–1070":"1020–1070","1035–1080":"1035–1080","about 1072":"umbes 1072","1080":"1080","about 1063":"umbes 1063","about 1074":"umbes 1074","before 1038":"enne 1038","1066":"1066","1020":"1020","1130":"1130","1086":"1086","1074":"1074","1096":"1096","1052":"1052","1050":"1050","1